	<h1>2. Setup</h1>
	<p>
		This chapter is theoretical and will prepare you for the Chapter 4 exercise, please read through.
	</p>
	<p>
		NOTICE: <strong>JS Core Framework</strong> is internally called &quot;<strong>Titan</strong>&quot;, therefore we will be using the &quot;Titan&quot; object when extending objects.
	</p>
	<p>
		&nbsp;
	</p>
	<h2>Adding JS Core to your Web Application</h2>
	<p>
		JS Core is contained in a single JavaScript file, in order to use it you have to download it and include it in your page.
	</p>
	<table class="wysiwyg-macro" data-macro-name="code" data-macro-parameters="language=html/xml" style="background-image: url(/plugins/servlet/confluence/placeholder/macro-heading?definition=e2NvZGU6bGFuZ3VhZ2U9aHRtbC94bWx9&amp;locale=en_GB&amp;version=2); background-repeat: no-repeat;" data-macro-body-type="PLAIN_TEXT">
	<tr>
		<td class="wysiwyg-macro-body">
			<pre>
				 &lt;head> &lt;script src="titan-dev-0.1.1.js">&lt;/script> &lt;/head>
			</pre>
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
	<h2>Basic Example</h2>
	<p>
		The following example demonstrates starting an application based on jsCore.
	</p>
	<table class="wysiwyg-macro" data-macro-name="code" data-macro-parameters="language=html/xml" style="background-image: url(/plugins/servlet/confluence/placeholder/macro-heading?definition=e2NvZGU6bGFuZ3VhZ2U9aHRtbC94bWx9&amp;locale=en_GB&amp;version=2); background-repeat: no-repeat;" data-macro-body-type="PLAIN_TEXT">
		<tr>
			<td class="wysiwyg-macro-body">
<pre>
&lt;html> 
	&lt;head>
		&lt;title>MyApplication&lt;/title> 
		&lt;script type="text/javascript" src="titan-dev-0.1.1.js">&lt;/script> 
		&lt;script type="text/javascript"> 
			require({
				baseUrl: 'src'
			}, ['domReady!', 'Application'], function (doc, Application) {
				var app = new Application({
					container: '#myContainer'
				});
				app.start();
			});
		&lt;/script> 
	&lt;/head> 
	&lt;body> 
		&lt;div id="myContainer">&lt;/div> 
	&lt;/body> 
&lt;/html>
</pre>
			</td>
		</tr>
	</table>
	<p>
		The above example will not execute without a valid application source (in this case Application.js file). We will learn how to create a basic application file in the next section.
	</p>
	<h2>Download JS Core</h2>
	<p>
		There are two versions of JS Core available:
	</p>
	<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
		<li>Production Version 1.1 - code is compressed and minified to run efficiently in your web application</li>
		<li>Development Version 1.1 - this is uncompressed (readable code) for testing and development</li>
	</ul>
